template.value:
You are an expert data engineer. Generate a production-ready parser for the following data sample.

Input format: {input_format} (auto-detect if 'auto-detect')
Target output format: {output_format}
Programming language: {output_language}
Extraction goal: {extraction_goal}

Sample data:
```
{sample_data}
```

Return ONLY a valid JSON object with this structure:
{{
  "detected_format": "json|csv|xml|yaml|toml|log|text|mixed",
  "detected_schema": {{
    "description": "plain English description of what the data contains",
    "fields": [
      {{"name": "field_name", "type": "str|int|float|bool|list|dict|datetime", "nullable": true/false, "example": "..."}}
    ],
    "record_count_in_sample": <integer>
  }},
  "parser_code": "complete runnable {output_language} code as a single string with \\n for newlines",
  "dependencies": ["list of pip packages to install"],
  "install_command": "pip install ...",
  "usage_example": "how to call the parser with the sample data",
  "test_cases": [
    {{"description": "...", "input": "...", "expected_output": "..."}}
  ],
  "edge_cases_handled": ["list of edge cases the parser handles"],
  "limitations": ["what the parser does NOT handle"]
}}

Parser code requirements:
- Complete, runnable, no placeholders
- Include type hints
- Include docstring
- Include error handling (try/except)
- Include a main() function that demonstrates usage
- For unstructured inputs (PDF, Word, HTML, logs, text): use the `unstructured` library
- For structured inputs (JSON, CSV, XML, YAML): use standard libraries
- Tests must be runnable with pytest

Return ONLY the JSON. No markdown fences. No explanation.
